                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">835.00/309: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Riddle</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-09-30T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 30, 1922—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. Your 61, September 29, noon.</p>
                <p>As it will be the new president who will receive you as President’s special
                    representative and the letter is to be handed by you to him, the Department
                    thinks it is properly addressed to him. This corresponds to course taken in case
                    of President Wilson’s special representative at the inauguration of present
                    president of Chile, which was not questioned, and credences of special
                    representatives of Latin American Governments to President Harding’s
                    inauguration, although antedating the event, were addressed to him and not to
                    President Wilson.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
